New Records: The Dodgers completed the biggest comeback in a World Series clinching victory.
Key Match Events: The Dodgers won the World Series with a 7-6 victory over the Yankees in Game 5.
Freddie Freeman drove in 12 runs during the series and was awarded the Willie Mays MVP award.
Blake Treinen pitched 2.1 innings with no runs allowed and three strikeouts.
The Yankees committed multiple errors, including a crucial catcher's interference call in the 8th inning.
Walker Buehler, a starter, pitched in the 9th inning to secure the win for the Dodgers.
Post-Match Reflections: Dave Roberts expressed pride in the team's performance, stating 'this trophy belongs to everybody'.
Freddie Freeman highlighted the significance of the World Series trophy over the MVP award.
Miscellaneous Highlights: The Dodgers celebrated their first non-shortened season title since 1988.
This victory marked the Dodgers' eighth World Series title in franchise history.
The Dodgers have now beaten New York in four World Series.
